			<li id="comment-6988" class="alt">
				<p class="comment-metadata"><strong>Paul Boos</strong> | 22-Mar-10 at 7:47 am | <a href="#comment-6988" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="permalink">Permalink</a> </p>
								<p>This is a great mechanism for working.  This is not at all saying this can not work, but one contextual item where a pull system may NOT work is if during Sprint Planning, you estimate when you need a particular user to help with refining the requirements (story).  You can&#8217;t just pull, because you &#8220;scheduled&#8221; that person at a particular time most likely for a reason (perhaps they weren&#8217;t available).  At the very least, it could become a problem as you would be giving them last minute notice.</p>
<p>Again, this is not to say this technique can&#8217;t work, but just to provide a case where it may be more difficult as a consideration for those thinking of using it.  If the user (and perhaps it is the product owner, but often he or she may not be) can be totally dedicated to the team or at least to that Sprint, then this could be problematic.</p>
<p>Great post and I&#8217;ll be looking for where I can apply these concepts.</p>
<p>Cheers!<br />
Paul</p>
			</li>
